The City of Tshwane has agreed to pay its municipal workers, a promised 6.25 percent salary increase, but says it can't afford the back pay it owes them. Pule Letshwiti has more. Courtesy #DStv403 JOHANNESBURG - The City of Tshwane has agreed to pay its municipal workers, a promised 6.25 percent salary increase, but says it can't afford the back pay it owes them. READ:Â Tshwane reaches wage deal with municipal workers The metro's administrators have again engaged in talks with the South African Municipal Workers Union (SAMWU), after negotiations broke down, leading to the city being brought to a standstill by protesting workers. Chaos erupted for a third consecutive day on Thursday, as workers blocked roads, vandalised state property, and forced shops to close down. The city says it is open to continuing talks, but the union says it will approach the courts, should back pay and salary scale adjustments not be included in a new deal. Watch the video above for more on this story.